# DRSearch Architecture and Global Guidelines

## Overall Architecture

DRSearch is a RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) application with the following components:

- **Frontend**: Next.js 13.5 React application with TypeScript and Chakra UI
- **Backend**: FastAPI Python application with LangChain integration
- **Vector Database**: PostgreSQL w/ PGvector extension or semantic/keyword search capabilities
- **Structured Database**: PostgreSQL for record management
- **Deployment**: Docker-based containerization

## Technology Stack

| Component | Technology |
|-----------|------------|
| Frontend | Next.js, React, TypeScript, Chakra UI |
| Backend | Python, FastAPI, LangChain, Poetry |
| Vector Search | Weaviate |
| Structured Data | PostgreSQL with pgvector |
| Testing | Jest, React Testing Library, Pytest, Playwright |
| Build/Deploy | Docker, docker-compose |
| Authentication | Azure AD JWT Bearer |

## Global Coding Conventions

### Type Safety

- All TypeScript code must use explicit types for function parameters, return values, and component props
- Python code must include type annotations (using standard library `typing` module)
- Avoid `any` type in TypeScript and `Optional[Any]` in Python wherever possible

### Testing Standards

- Backend coverage target: >80% for core application logic
- Frontend coverage target: >70% for component and utility code
- End-to-end tests must cover all critical user flows
- Tests should use data-testid attributes for frontend element selection
- Mock external dependencies to ensure test isolation

### Code Formatting

- JavaScript/TypeScript: Prettier with default configuration
- Python: Black formatter with default 88-character line length
- All code must pass linting before merge (ESLint for JS/TS, flake8 for Python)

### Documentation

- All public APIs must include docstrings
- React components should include JSDoc comments for props
- Complex algorithms and business logic need explanatory comments
- README files must be kept up-to-date in all main directories

### CI/CD Expectations

- All tests must pass before merge to main branch
- Coverage reports are generated for each PR
- Docker builds are tested in CI to ensure containerization works
- E2E tests run against the fully composed application
